ong elites in medieval Egypt. Written by the unemployed bureaucrat 'Uthman ibn Ibrahim al-Nabulusi, it contains a wealth of little-known historical anecdotes, unusual religious opinions, obscure and witty poetry, and humorous cultural satire. Leaving no rhetorical stone unturned, al-Nabulusi pours his deep knowledge of history, law, and literature into the work—addressed to the Ayyubid sultan—as he argues against the employment of Coptic and Jewish officials. Written at a time when much of the inter-communal animosity of the era was conditioned by fierce competition for scarce resources that were increasingly controlled by an ideologically committed Sunni Muslim state, The Sword of Ambition reminds us that “religious” conflict must always be considered in its broader historical perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAdministrative agencieszEgyptvEarly works to 1800. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aJackson, Sherman 'Abd al-Hakim.1 aJackson, Sherman ʿAbd Al-Ḥakĩm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYarbrough, Luke.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831107227270 cprintz978147982478640uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479839766.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479839766423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479839766/original  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOO